To generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document, you can use the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example of how to create a simple document with a table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Packages for formatting and customization
\usepackage{titlesec}
\usepackage{lipsum}

% Customize the section formatting
\titleformat{\section}
  {\normalfont\fontsize{14}{15}\bfseries}{\thesection}{1em}{}

% Customize the TOC formatting
\titleformat{\section}
  {\normalfont\fontsize{12}{15}\bfseries}{\contentslabel{1.5em}}{0em}{}
\titlespacing*{\section}
  {0pt}{3.5ex plus 1ex minus .2ex}{2.3ex plus .2ex}

\begin{document}

% Print the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Add some sections
\section{Introduction}
\lipsum[1-2]

\section{Methods}
\lipsum[3-4]

\section{Results}
\lipsum[5-6]

\section{Discussion}
\lipsum[7-8]

\end{document}
```

In this example, we use the `titlesec` and `lipsum` packages to format the sections and add some dummy text. The `\titleformat` command is used to customize the appearance of the sections in the document and the table of contents. The `\tableofcontents` command is used to print the table of contents itself.

When you compile this document with a LATEX compiler, the table of contents will be generated automatically based on the sections you've defined. You can customize the appearance of the table of contents by adjusting the formatting commands in the `\titleformat` command.

To draw a chessboard in LATEX, we can use the `pspicture` environment from the `pstricks` package and the `chessfss` package to typeset the chess symbols. Here's an example LATEX code that takes a FEN notation as an input and generates a chessboard based on that:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{pstricks}
\usepackage{chessfss}

\newcommand{\generateBoard}[1]{%
  \begin{pspicture}(-0.5,-0.5)(8.5,8.5)
    \psset{unit=1cm}
    \multido{\i=1+1}{8}{\psline(\i,1)(\i,8)}
    \multido{\i=1+1}{8}{\psline(1,\i)(8,\i)}
    \multido{\i=1+1}{8}{\multido{\j=1+1}{8}{\chesspiece{\i\j}[\getpiece{\i\j}]}}
    \psset{linecolor=black}
    \multido{\i=1+1}{8}{\psline(\i,1)(\i,8)}
    \multido{\i=1+1}{8}{\psline(1,\i)(8,\i)}
  \end{pspicture}
}

\newcommand{\getpiece}[1]{\ifcase#1\or ♙\or ♟\or ♔\or ♕\or ♖\or ♗\or ♘\or ♙\or ♜\or ♛\or ♝\or ♞\or ♟\fi}

\begin{document}

\def\fen{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\generateBoard{\fen}

\end{document}
```

In this code, the `\generateBoard` command takes a FEN notation as an argument and generates a chessboard based on that. The `\getpiece` command maps the piece codes in the FEN notation to the corresponding chess symbols.

To use this code, simply replace the `\fen` command with the FEN notation you want to display. For example, the code above generates a board with the starting position of a standard chess game.

Note that you will need to compile this code with a LATEX compiler that supports the `pstricks` package, such as `pdflatex` with the `--shell-escape` flag.

